T1  - Sex Discrimination Against Women in Initial Placement Decisions: A Laboratory Investigation
AU  - Taylor, M. Susan
AU  - Ilgen, Daniel R.
Y1  - 1981/12/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256182
DO  - 10.5465/256182
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 859
EP  - 865
VL  - 24
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article focuses on a study which investigated sexual discrimination against women within selection decisions made for traditionally male positions. The authors hypothesize that female employees would be rated as more suitable for placement in less challenging jobs than in more challenging jobs. They also believe that people who work with a competent, high performing female in a typically male position would be display less of a tendency to rate an unknown female candidate as more suitable for initial placement in a low challenge position that a high challenge one than people who work with a high performing male. Results showed proved both hypotheses.
AB  - The article focuses on a study which investigated sexual discrimination against women within selection decisions made for traditionally male positions. The authors hypothesize that female employees would be rated as more suitable for placement in less challenging jobs than in more challenging jobs. They also believe that people who work with a competent, high performing female in a typically male position would be display less of a tendency to rate an unknown female candidate as more suitable for initial placement in a low challenge position that a high challenge one than people who work with a high performing male. Results showed proved both hypotheses.
